title: For Sale:  harrington & richardson self-loading .32acp
postcontent:
For sale serious offers only" one listed on gunbroker for 495, and this one is much better condition wise! in westminster  or trade for a beretta model 1934 in .32 or .380 - is my self-loading pistol was manufactured during the period 1910-1914,under agreement with webley & scott of birmingham england, and it is in fact, the webley .25 "hammerless" model of 1909.patents were taken out in the US in 1907 and 1909, principally covering the use of twin recoil springs, and the H&R differs from the webley in many ways.
the webley is hammerless in name only,since it used an internal hammer, and the H&r lockwork was rather different than the webley, probably as a matter of manufacturing convenience.more obvious is the shaping of the barrel and slide; in the webley pattern the slide is open topped with a bridge carrying the front sight.as a result the barrel is slender so the bridge can pass over it on recoil.
the H&R model uses an open topped slide without a bridge,and the barrel rear section is built up to continue the contours of the slide;there are no rear sights fitted. the external contours of the H&R are more generally radiussed than those of the webley, and the grips are fitted in a different manner.
it was believed that there was little demand for the .25 model and few were made..H&R also produced a .32 model which, while based on webley practice, was not a counterpart of any webley and scott model. it was 'hammerless' ( i.e internal hammer)model with open topped slide and extended barrel, and a short grip safety at the rear of the butt. it also used a coil spring recoil spring above the bolt, instead of the webley v-spring system. this model appeared shortly befor the first world war, and continued to me made into the early 1920's.
this one is clean as a whistlein and out with original holster minor wear , no rust, no pitting. shine in bore strong rifleing. perfect grips 8+1 capacity. 3 0 3 4 3 0 8 1 9 2  make a serious offer

title: For Sale:  1865 Civil War Confederate File Bowie Knife COA and Appraisal $14,500 trade
postcontent:
Dated 1865, more 145 years ago - when the Confederate Army began running out of real weapon supplies, they began making weapons out of everything they could find. This fine example from the Civil War consists of a 6" blade made from a file making the entire specimen about 10". Coagulated blood rusted onto the blade of this piece makes it especially valuable to collectors and dealers.
Comes with a Certificate of Authenticity and an Appraisal - both stating value at $14,500.

The COA (obtained from a historical researcher with over 35 years experience) states "Your knife with a 6" blade and 10" overall length is a manufacture made 'file' knife in the Confederacy. Many file knives of assorted sizes and markings were more common between 1863 and 1865 due to the lack of proper material for production.
The company name, along with CSA and the year of the manufacture (1865) appears undoubtedly authentic. It is rarely seen where the company nae, date and origin is still in tact on a wood handle. "The knife appears to be well cared for and used but not abused, putting most of the value in the handle itself.
"...It appears that the dark pitting on the blade and handle is from 'blood rust'. Blood rust is the deposit of coagulated blood allowed to remain on the surface causing the irregular pattern of rust pitting from the concentration of salt content in blood."
Knife comes in a display case with a miniature copy of the appraisal for display, and the full size copy as well as the COA will be sold with the item.
Willing to entertain all cash offers and trade offers for things such as cars, trucks, motorcycles (HD preferred but not limited), land, real estate, gold, electronic lots, GUNS and other items of value, let me know via email, thanks.
